ODE XI.

‘Do not trouble yourself with foreign polities, Quintius, nor with schemes of business. Life wants very little, and it is flying fast: spring flowers die and moons wane. Do not weary yourself over plans as if things remained for ever. Better crown with roses our hair-s already whitening with age, and drink and play while we may.'
